CAIT data set of global Green house gas emmision is acquired from - http://datasets.wri.org/dataset/cait-country .The CAIT Country GHG emissions collection applies a consistent methodology to create a six-gas, multi-sector, and internationally comparable data set for 186 countries.

DECOMPOSITION

TREND THE GHG emmision follows a increasing pattern overtime

Seasonality yearly data no seasonality here

tghg_ma <- ts(na.omit(subt$ghg_ma5), frequency=5) 
#taking 5 years as a frequeny and will build model around it

decomp = stl(tghg_ma, s.window="periodic" ,)
deseasonal_ghg <- seasadj(decomp)
plot(decomp)

#trend could easily be seen almost not too much noise 


#Arima model requires a stationary series

adf.test(tghg_ma, alternative = "stationary")
## 
##  Augmented Dickey-Fuller Test
## 
## data:  tghg_ma
## Dickey-Fuller = -1.1467, Lag order = 2, p-value = 0.8974
## alternative hypothesis: stationary
#Autocorrelation plots for chosing Arima parametres

Acf(tghg_ma, main='')

Pacf(tghg_ma, main='')

Creating models to find best fit

m1 <- auto.arima(deseasonal_ghg, seasonal=FALSE)
m1
## Series: deseasonal_ghg 
## ARIMA(0,2,0) 
## 
## sigma^2 estimated as 284.3:  log likelihood=-72.14
## AIC=146.28   AICc=146.55   BIC=147.11
#model is ok because no major corelation can be seen from ACF andPACF checking for '6'
tsdisplay(residuals(m1), lag.max=10, main='(0,2,0) Model Residuals') 

m2 <- arima(deseasonal_ghg, order=c(1,1,6))

m2
## 
## Call:
## arima(x = deseasonal_ghg, order = c(1, 1, 6))

#m2 model with  6 is better and shows no correlation

fcast <- forecast(m2, h=15)
plot(fcast)

OPTIONAL: Did you create any models with your dataset?

Discuss the and limitations of your model.

ARIMA (Autoregressive integrated moving average) is very widely used model time series analysis this model Also the Data was Non-seasonal in nature so non seasonal - Arima(p,d,q) model was used. The model is built on a single variable to analyze its future values by using previous values . The optimal model was found out to be ARIMA(1,1,6) [AR=1 , I=1 , MA=6] .

STRENGTH-

Optimal for Univariate forecast of a Time series data Uses lags(previous values) to help possible predict future values 80% confidence limits shaded in darker blue, and 95% in lighter blue.

WEAKNESS-

The forecast broadens and becomes less relaible as time increase

Plot Two

Description Two

The plot dipicts the trend followed by some of the countries over the years in diffrent fields such as Transport , Manufacturing etc .China is mostly at the to in Emmision . The trend is in the Increasing direction mostly but Japan is showing a decreasing trend in variables such as Transport emmision , Emmision due to waste which is very rare given this dataset.

Plot Three

Description Three

Forecast of timeseries data of India pridicting next 15 values for total ghg emissions. 80% confidence limits shaded in darker blue, and 95% in lighter blue. Longer term forecasts will usually have more uncertainty, as the model gives further future values it will become more and more uncertain this could be seen as the spread increases along the xaxis(time)

Bivariate analysis helped in identifieng the anomalities / diffrent patterns in the Data This was very Useful as the data was highly corelated and it would mostly be a increasing linear Trend. Finnaly The Multivariate Analysis brought about some meaningful analytics and some infrences Could be drawn from it. Time series Data was bit diffrent Than a Normal Data and hence modeling it was a chalange at first but with the right model it was very effect to Analayze and produce prictions for this Data The huge diffrences in emmision of countries like Japan And China Were Note worthy Though they also have diffrence in Population and Land-Mass But Japan had a significantly more GDP Percapita Than China.
The Analysis of of Emmisions with Various Economic and social parametres could be done to produce more insights .
